**3. What is the Document Object Model (DOM)?** 
The DOM stands for Document Object Model. It is a tree-like structure created by the browser 
when a webpage loads. It represents the HTML document as objects that can be changed. It 
connects the HTML code to JavaScript so you can build dynamic pages. With the DOM, 
JavaScript can easily add, remove, or edit elements. It acts like a bridge between your webpage 
content and your script. 
**4. What is the difference between <div> and <span> elements?** 
The <div> element is a block-level element used for crea ng layouts. It always starts on a new 
line and takes up the full width of the page. The <span> element is an inline element used for 
small parts of text. It does not start on a new line and only takes up needed space. You use 
<div> for big sec ons and <span> for specific words inside a paragraph. They are both non
seman c elements used for styling. 
